As a 3rd-year Computer Science student aiming to become a Full Stack Developer, it's essential to assess your technical skills, behavioral fit, and problem-solving abilities. Here are three technical questions, two HR/behavioral questions, and a coding challenge tailored to your skills and interests:

### Technical Questions

1. **How do you handle state management in a JavaScript application, and what libraries or frameworks do you use for this purpose?**

Ideal Answer: The candidate should discuss the importance of state management, mention libraries like Redux or MobX, and explain how they integrate these into their applications.

Core Criteria: Understanding of JavaScript, familiarity with state management concepts, and knowledge of relevant libraries.

2. **Explain the difference between null and undefined in JavaScript. Provide an example of when you would use each.**

Ideal Answer: The candidate should clearly define null and undefined, discuss their differences, and provide code examples demonstrating their usage.

Core Criteria: Proficiency in JavaScript, understanding of primitive data types, and ability to provide practical examples.

3. **How does CSS grid differ from flexbox, and when would you choose one over the other in your web development projects?**

Ideal Answer: The candidate should explain the basic principles of both CSS grid and flexbox, discuss their use cases, and provide scenarios where one might be preferred over the other.

Core Criteria: Knowledge of HTML/CSS, understanding of layout management, and ability to make informed design decisions.

### HR/Behavioral Questions (Using the STAR Method)

1. **Tell me about a project where you had to learn a new technology or skill to meet the requirements. How did you go about learning it, and what was the outcome?**

Ideal Answer: The candidate should describe a specific project, explain the new skill or technology they learned (e.g., a JavaScript framework), discuss their learning process (e.g., tutorials, documentation), and highlight the successful outcome of the project.

Core Criteria: Ability to learn quickly, adaptability, and achievement of project goals.

2. **Describe a situation where you worked in a team on a programming project. What was your role, and how did you contribute to the team's efforts?**

Ideal Answer: The candidate should outline their role in the team, explain their responsibilities, discuss how they contributed to the project (e.g., coding, debugging, design), and describe how the team worked together to achieve their goals.

Core Criteria: Teamwork, communication skills, and contribution to project success.

### Coding Challenge

**Prompt:** Create a simple web page that displays a list of books. Each book should have a title, author, and publication year. The list should be sorted alphabetically by title. Use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

**Constraints:**

- Use a static array of book objects in JavaScript.
- Implement a simple sorting function in JavaScript.
- Style the list using CSS to make it visually appealing.

**Standard Solution:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Book List</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .book-list {
            list-style: none;
            padding: 0;
        }
        .book {
            padding: 10px;
            border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
        .book:last-child {
            border-bottom: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Book List</h1>
    <ul id="bookList" class="book-list"></ul>

    <script>
        // Static array of book objects
        const books = [
            { title: "To Kill a Mockingbird", author: "Harper Lee", year: 1960 },
            { title: "1984", author: "George Orwell", year: 1949 },
            { title: "Pride and Prejudice", author: "Jane Austen", year: 1813 },
        ];

        // Sort the books array by title
        books.sort((a, b) => a.title.localeCompare(b.title));

        // Get the book list element
        const bookList = document.getElementById('bookList');

        // Function to render the book list
        function renderBookList() {
            bookList.innerHTML = '';
            books.forEach(book => {
                const bookElement = document.createElement('li');
                bookElement.classList.add('book');
                bookElement.innerHTML = `${book.title} by ${book.author}, ${book.year}`;
                bookList.appendChild(bookElement);
            });
        }

        // Render the book list
        renderBookList();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Explanation:** This solution creates a simple web page that displays a sorted list of books. It uses JavaScript to sort the array of book objects by title and then renders the list using HTML and CSS for styling.

**Instant Feedback:** The candidate's solution should demonstrate a clear understanding of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. The code should be well-organized, readable, and correctly implement the sorting functionality. The candidate's ability to follow instructions, attention to detail, and coding skills will be evaluated.
